# Code Search with vfs

`vfs` is a locally installed binary that parses source files and prints exported function/type signatures with bodies stripped. It supports **Go** (via `go/ast`), **JavaScript**, **TypeScript**, **JSX**, and **TSX** (via tree-sitter). It is faster and cheaper (fewer tokens) than reading full files or grepping raw source.

## When to use vfs

- Searching for function signatures, method signatures, class/interface/type declarations, or API surface.
- Exploring an unfamiliar codebase to see what's exported.
- Finding which file defines a specific handler, service method, component, or hook.

```bash
vfs .                          # all exported sigs in current project
vfs ./internal ./pkg           # scan specific Go directories
vfs ./src/components           # scan React/TS components
vfs ./internal -f HandleLogin  # filter to matching signatures
vfs handler.go                 # single file
vfs ./src -f useAuth           # find a React hook
```

## When NOT to use vfs

- Searching inside function bodies, string literals, or comments -- use `grep`/`rg`.
- Searching file types not supported (CSS, SQL, YAML, etc.) -- use `grep`/`rg`.
- Reading full implementation details -- use the Read tool after locating the file via vfs.

## Workflow

1. Run `vfs <path> -f <pattern>` to locate the function and its file.
2. Use the Read tool on the specific file and line range for implementation details.

## Supported file types

| Language   | Extensions                         |
|------------|------------------------------------|
| Go         | `.go`                              |
| JavaScript | `.js`, `.mjs`, `.cjs`, `.jsx`      |
| TypeScript | `.ts`, `.mts`, `.cts`, `.tsx`      |
